<title>CARING FOR OUR CHILDREN</title>

<body>

<center><img src="/townhall/FRC/infocus/infocus.gif">

<p>

<h2>CARING FOR OUR CHILDREN</h2></center>

<p>

A recent Census Bureau report states that the majority of preschool
children are cared for in a home environment while their mother
works, while school-aged children are typically in school during
their mother's working hours.

<p>

Sixty-three percent of preschool children of employed women spend
their mother's working hours in a home environment,[1] 51.8 percent
of whom are spending time with either their father or grandparent.
Of all preschool children, 15.9 percent are cared for by their
fathers while their mother works;  16.5 percent are cared for
by a grandparent.  Another relative cares for 8.8 percent of preschool
children.  Seventeen percent are cared for by a non-relative at
the provider's home.[2] Only 29.9 percent of all children under
the age of 5 rely upon an organized day care facility for care.[3]

<p>

This data also supports the finding that mothers of school-aged
children work part-time -- 74 percent of children between 5 and
14 years of age are at school while their mother works.  Six percent
of preschool children are with their mothers while they work.
A 1993 Roper poll conducted on behalf of Family Circle magazine
found that in 55 percent of households the child's parent or guardian
usually cared for children under 14 when they were not in school.
Twelve percent were cared for by a grandparent.  Comparatively,
13 percent were in a day care, preschool, or after school program
during non-school hours.[4]

<p>

Few statistics indicate how many children are in the care of an
at-home mother, even though it has been documented that children
reared at home by a parent fare far better in life-long cognitive
ability.[5] There are, however, some demonstrative statistics: 
40.2 percent of divorced, separated and widowed mothers of children
under 6 years old don't work, and 40.1 percent of married mothers
of children under 6 years old don't work.[6]

<p><br>

<center><h4>Number of Children, in 1,000's</h4>

<p><hr width=40%><pre>
Father:  CH                  1585
Grandparent:  CH              649
Other Relative:  CH           328
Non-Relative:  CH             492
Grandparent:  PH              996
Other Relative:  PH           543
Non-Relative:  PH            1645
Day Care                     1823
Nursery                      1149
School Activity                16
In School                      95
Self Care                       0
Mother Care                   616

<hr width=40%>
CH:  Child's Home   
PH:  Provider's Home
</pre></center><p>

-- 4/17/96

<p><hr><p>

