<html>

<title>ON BEING AN AMERICAN</title>

<body>

<center><img src="/townhall/FRC/perspective/perspective.gif">

<p>

<h2>ON BEING AN AMERICAN</h2>

<p><hr size=3 width=50%><p>

<i>by</i>

<p>

<i>Gracie S. Hsu</i></center>

<p>

Immigration reform is a hot topic today, and it's mostly fueled
by the real concern that illegal aliens are taking jobs and undercutting
wages for American citizens.  But, in the zeal to combat illegal
immigration, there has been an unfortunate side-effect --  too
often legal and illegal immigrants have been lumped together under
the category of &quot;foreign-born.&quot;

<p>

This use of &quot;foreign-born&quot; is troubling because it furthers
the notion that legal immigrants are &quot;one of them&quot; and
not &quot;one of us.&quot;

<p>

But legal immigrants <I>are</I> &quot;one of us.&quot;  Virtually
<I>every</I> American -- whether first-generation American or
10th-generation American -- has an immigrant heritage.  Legal
immigration (whether in the 1780s, 1880s or 1980s) has helped
America flourish.

<p>

Henry and Eunice are two such examples.  In August 1961, Henry
arrived in America at the age of 25.  Having graduated from the
most prestigious university in Taiwan, he was one of a select
few to be granted student visas to the U.S.  He did not hail from
a privileged background (he was the only one of seven siblings
to attend college), but he wanted to come to America because he
firmly believed that America was and is &quot;the land of opportunity.&quot;
He was eventually enabled to come to the U.S. because his eldest
sister, recognizing the opportunities America would afford her
brother, generously lent him all the savings that she had earned
from her job laundering other people's clothes so that he could
afford the cost of his plane ticket.

<p>

Since Henry came to America with virtually nothing, he spent his
first night at a local YMCA.  On his second day, he contacted
another immigrant friend who helped him find a place to live and
a dishwashing job paying $10 a day.  Later, Henry met and married
his wife Eunice (a Taiwanese immigrant who came to America on
a student visa to study physics), and they both worked to pay his 
way through graduate school -- he as a dishwasher and lab technician, 
and she as a clerical worker.

<p>

Neither of them has ever collected welfare or sought financial
aid from the government.  Instead, these two immigrants have worked
hard to fulfill the American dream.  Henry has an accomplished
record as a professional cheminal engineer for more than 20 years
and now manages his own real estate enterprise.  Henry and Eunice
have become homeowners, and they helped found a church in Los
Angeles that now has more than 30 branches around the world.

<p>

While America has certainly granted this couple economic opportunity,
it has more importantly given them freedom -- freedom of speech,
religion, and assembly without fear of reprisal.  For example,
for many years, Henry was very active in calling on the United
States to acknowledge Taiwan as a free and independent nation
and to support its fledgling movement towards democracy.  But
while his political activism left him blacklisted by the ruling
Taiwanese government, he could freely express his views to American
politicians as well as activate others who shared his views on
the grass-roots level.

<p>

Henry and Eunice not only exercise the freedoms given to them
by the United States, they also recognize that &quot;freedom is
not free.&quot;  Thus, they taught their children never to take
these freedoms for granted, but to appreciate, cherish, and defend
them.  Perhaps that is why one of their daughters was the first
Taiwanese-American female to graduate from West Point and is now
a captain in the U.S. Army.

<p>

America is unique among nations because its citizens, unlike those
of other countries, are bound together not by a shared ethnic
heritage or a common religion.  Rather, Americans share a set
of principles and an idealism which inspired the Declaration of
Independence and the U.S. Constitution.  So while both Henry and
Eunice have learned to speak English fluently and their children
have all settled in areas far from the ethnic familiarity of Southern
California -- South Dakota, North Carolina, and Washington, D.C.
-- they are Americans not for these external symbols of assimilation,
but because they have pledged their allegiance to the common principles
which make America &quot;one nation under God, indivisible, with
liberty and justice for all.&quot;

<p>

Admittedly, America has not always lived up to these high ideals,
as Henry and Eunice can well attest.  Indeed, they have experienced
the sting of racism firsthand -- from being denied service at
restaurants to being ridiculed for their accents to even being
implicitly denied entrance into the residential community of their
choice because the real estate agent made it clear that she did
not want &quot;people like them&quot; moving into her neighborhood.

<p>

But the fact remains that this couple chose to adopt America as
their own country.  And because they chose deliberately, with
great sacrifice, they don't take its privileges for granted.

<p>

Historians have long acknowledged and celebrated the manifold
contributions of our immigrant ancestors to this country -- economically,
intellectually, demographically, and culturally.  But to my mind,
the most significant contribution of these two immigrants I call
Mom and Dad is that they modeled for me, better than anyone else
I know, what it is to be an American.

<p>

-- 3/5/96

<p>

<center>***</center>

<p>

<i>Gracie S. Hsu, M.H.S., is a policy analyst for the Family Research
Council, a Washington, D.C.-based research and educational organization.</i>

<p>

<center>
