<html>

<title>JUDICIAL TERRORISM: A MORAL CRISIS</title>

<body>

<center><img src="/townhall/FRC/perspective/perspective.gif">

<p>

<h2>JUDICIAL TERRORISM:<br>
A MORAL CRISIS</h2>

<p><hr size=3 width=50%><p>

<i>by</i>

<p>

<i>Robert L. Maginnis and Robert H. Knight</i></center>

<p>

Coloradans voted 54 to 46 percent in 1992 to approve a statewide
referendum that barred the state and local governments from enacting
laws that gave &quot;special rights&quot; to homosexuals.  In
a sweeping and unprecedented move, the Supreme Court on May 20,
1996, declared Colorado's &quot;special rights&quot; prohibition
unconstitutional.

<p>

The Supreme Court's decision striking down Colorado's law may
prove to be the cultural equivalent of <I>Roe v. Wade</I>.  That
1973 decision has resulted in the deaths of 30 million unborn
Americans.  This decision may result in the death of the traditional
family and the institution of marriage -- the very core of our
society.

<p>

Writing for the minority, Justice Antonin Scalia said there is
&quot;no foundation in American constitutional law&quot; for the
court's ruling.

<p>

Using strange (but politically correct) reasoning, the high court
equates limiting special treatment for homosexuals with denying
them equal protection under the constitution.  The fact is, no
one proposes to deny homosexuals their constitutional rights.
Colorado citizens merely chose to deny the establishment of another
class of citizens with more rights than other citizens.  Such
legal status has been reserved for the truly disadvantaged.  As
a group, however, homosexuals are renowned for being politically,
financially and otherwise advantaged.

<p>

Denying preferential treatment to a group whose identifying marker
may be criminal behavior can hardly be construed as violating
an individual's civil rights.  To do so would be a serious blow
to democracy.  To say that disallowing special treatment is the
same as denying equal protection is ludicrous.  Any group that
loses a political battle at the state level could be said to have
&quot;lost&quot; equal protection.

<p>

The court's decision opens the flood gates to potential litigation.
Any law based on the majority's moral beliefs is subject to being
labeled as &quot;hate-based&quot; or &quot;bigoted,&quot; and
groups affected by such laws are likely to seek legal redress.

<p>

Five states have constitutional prohibitions against polygamy.
With the new decision, people with a polygamous &quot;orientation&quot;
may logically complain that they have been singled out for unequal
treatment.  This same line of reasoning could be used by groups
identified by criminal behavior such as pedophilia.

<p>

Scalia wrote, &quot;The Court's disposition today suggests that
these provisions [polygamy prohibitions] are unconstitutional...unless,
of course, polygamists for some reason have fewer constitutional
rights than homosexuals.&quot;

<p>

The court's majority opinion also insults Coloradans by suggesting
that they are hateful. That's absurd. The will of the people
was to defend traditional sexual mores against a politically powerful
minority.  The homosexual rights agenda seeks to force Americans
to embrace their morality by using the law to declare homosexuality
the moral equivalent of heterosexuality.

<p>

Colorado, where sodomy is no longer illegal, made no attempt to
restrict homosexual conduct which is still illegal in 20 states
and in the U.S. armed forces.  Although many states have removed
criminal statutes for sodomy (the defining homosexual behavior)
the act is still widely held as being morally wrong and socially
harmful.

<p>

The court's majority opinion ignored the 1986 <I>Bowers v. Hardwick</I>
decision in which Georgia's sodomy law was declared constitutional.
If laws against sodomy are constitutional, then why must preferential
treatment be accorded to those whose defining characteristic is
their self-identification with the practice of sodomy?

<p>

After all, there is no reliable evidence that homosexuality is
genetic.  It is a behavior tragically afflicting less than two
percent of the population.  It is recognized by most psychiatric
associations around the world as pathological or as a sexual deviation.
According to a 1993 <I>Psychiatric News</I> report, only three
psychiatric associations out of 125 in the world -- including
the United States -- have declared homosexuality normal.

<p>

The <I>Romer v. Evans</I> decision is a severe blow to America's
moral heritage and will be used by homosexual rights activists
to further separate the family from its traditional Judeo-Christian
roots.  They will use this ruling to force religiously motivated
people to subsidize and promote behavior that they find morally
bankrupt and against their most deeply held beliefs.

<p>

The next target of the gay rights activists is the Defense of
Marriage Act (DOMA), which is now before Congress.  Given the
<I>Romer</I> decision, the high court may label DOMA as 
&quot;hate-mongering&quot; and rule it unconstitutional as well.
Think about that -- marriage itself constituting &quot;bigotry&quot;
because it requires both sexes.

<p>

It's time for Congress to assert its rightful place in the running
of our nation.  DOMA would send a strong message that Americans
will not knuckle under to judicial terrorism.  Its swift passage
is now more imperative than ever.

<p>
-- 5/24/96
<p>

<center>***</center>

<p>

<i>Robert Maginnis is a senior policy analyst and Robert Knight
is the Director for Cultural Studies for the Family Research Council,
a Washington, D.C.-based research and education organization.</i>

<p>

