<html>
<body>
<title>The Strange Transformation of the Supreme Court's Privacy Doctrine</title>
<center><img src="/townhall/FRC/podium/podium.gif">
<h2><i>MEYER</i>, HOW YOU'VE GROWN:<br>
THE STRANGE TRANSFORMATION<br>
OF THE SUPREME COURT'S<br>
PRIVACY DOCTRINE</h2>
<p><hr size=3 width=50%><p>
<i>by</i>
<p>
<i>David M. Wagner</i></center>
<p>
<i>This paper is the text of a lecture given at Molloy College, Rockville Center, 
NY, on April 21, 1994.</i>
<p>
The &quot;constitutional right of privacy&quot;
was much talked about back in 1987, when Robert Bork -- a nominee
who had been considered unbeatable because of his sterling legal
record -- was, in fact, beaten, largely because his opponents
focused on the fact that he had critiqued the Court's privacy
cases.  Judge Bork's defeat should have meant, at a minimum, that
privacy, whatever exactly it is, is highly valued by the American
people.
<p>
Supporters of Judge Bork countered that the word &quot;privacy&quot;
was merely that year's euphemism for abortion.  They were right,
insofar as the cases that Judge Bork had gotten in the most trouble
for critiquing were <i>Griswold v. Connecticut</i>,[1] in which the Court
struck down a statute that banned the use of contraceptives, and
<i>Roe v. Wade</i>,[2] which, of course, is the foundational case for a
constitutional right of abortion.
<p>
But the constitutional right
of privacy did not start with these cases.  It started in a very
different kind of cultural environment and was deployed in defense
of very different values.  The story of its origins and subsequent
development tells us a lot about the changes in the thinking of
our nation's elites between the early 1920's and today.
<p>
The privacy cases trace their origin to a series of Supreme Court cases in
the 1920's that all dealt, in one way or another, with the rights
of parents to direct the education of their children.  Included
in this series were <i>Meyer v. Nebraska</i>[3] and <i>Bartels v. Iowa</i>,[4] 
in which the Court struck down statutes that banned the teaching
of foreign languages below the ninth grade.
<p>
(You might wonder how such statutes got passed in the first place.  Remember that
this was in the early 20's, and passions were still high from
World War I.  Notice that the names of the
plaintiffs, Meyer and Bartels, were both German.)
<p>
In the later cases of the series, <i>Pierce v. Society of Sisters</i>[5] 
and <i>Farrington v. Tokushige</i>,[6] the Court struck down statutes that were 
aimed at eliminating private education.  The statute struck down in <i>Pierce</i>
had banned private schools outright by mandating children's attendance
at public schools.  The statute struck down in <i>Farrington</i> imposed
an extensive and intrusive regulatory regime on so-called &quot;foreign
language schools&quot; in Hawaii.  (It appears that this statute
was primarily an anti-Japanese move, since schools that used the
Hawaiian language were not considered &quot;foreign,&quot; while
Japanese was by far the leading minority language.)  Of these
four cases, two of them -- <i>Meyer</i> and <i>Pierce</i> -- came to be seen
as the leading ones, and the theory that sees the parent-child
relationship as protected by the Due Process Clause is sometimes
called the <i>Meyer-Pierce</i> doctrine.
<p>
In those days, the Supreme Court
was much in the habit of striking down social legislation and
economic regulation.  The Court was fervently committed to free
market economics and to the philosophy of individualism that goes
with such economics, and it frequently resorted to the argument
that the Constitution itself prohibits laws that regulate the
economic marketplace.  In some cases it used the Constitution's
Contracts Clause[7] of Article II Section 10 of the Constitution,
but it relied even more heavily on the Due Process Clause of the
14th Amendment, which prohibits states from taking life, liberty,
or property without due process of law.
<p>
Some jurists, including Justice Oliver Wendell Holmes,[8] offered the critique 
that was later offered by Robert Bork and others -- that the Due Process Clause
focuses on process rather than substance and does not give the
Court the power to strike down regulations enacted according to
fair procedures.  Holmes, in 1905, like Bork in 1987, stood up
for &quot;the right of a [political] majority to embody their
opinions in law.&quot;  But that other great majority -- a majority
of the Court -- held throughout the early 20th century that the
Due Process Clause protects more than mere due process; it also
prohibits some types of legislation altogether, and may, therefore,
be said to protect &quot;due substance&quot; as well as due process.
<p>
This doctrine, which came to be known as &quot;substantive due
process,&quot; is also the doctrinal matrix of the parents' rights
cases.  The conventional explanation today of the Court's solicitude
both for economic freedom and for parental authority is that the
Court was protecting a class system that depended both on patriarchal
authority and on unrestrained capitalism.[9]  But the need for &quot;hidden
agenda&quot; theories diminishes once one realizes that household
and marketplace are not antitheses, but different points along
a continuum of interconnected human relationships.  The very term
&quot;economics&quot; comes from the Greek &quot;oikos,&quot;
meaning &quot;household.&quot;  (Also underlying the Court's concern
was the right of private school teachers to earn their living
at their chosen profession.[10])
<p>
In the 30's, substantive due process
was a major obstacle to FDR's reforms.  Regardless of where one
stands on the merits of FDR's programs, one does have to recognize
that the electorate wanted change and was getting tired of unelected
and life-tenured judges using esoteric constitutional doctrines
to substitute their philosophy for the philosophy embraced by
the majority of the nation.   FDR's Attorney General, Robert Jackson,
spoke eloquently of how the Court had substituted its own views
of the Constitution for what the Constitution actually says. 
Eventually FDR put Jackson and other liberal jurists on the Court;
the doctrine of substantive due process officially went into discredit
in 1937; and a former clerk to Justice Jackson is now Chief Justice
of the United States.
<p>
Only one strand of substantive due process
survived 1937 -- the <i>Meyer-Pierce</i> doctrine.  It's true that the
Court placed an outer limit on that doctrine in 1944, in <i>Prince
v. Massachusetts</i>,[11] in which it held that <i>Meyer</i> and <i>Pierce</i> 
do not exempt parents or guardians from the child labor laws.  This case
involved a child's legal guardian who wanted the child to help
her distribute religious literature.  The Court turned aside both
a parents' rights claim and a free exercise of religion claim.
 To this day, <i>Prince</i> is always the first case cited by government
attorneys defending some state action against a constitutional
challenge by parents.  But even in <i>Prince</i>, the Court went out
of its way to clarify that it was not overruling the <i>Meyer-Pierce</i>
doctrine.  It said:
<p>
<blockquote>It is cardinal with us that the custody,
care and nurture of the child reside first in the parents, whose
primary function and freedom include preparation for obligations
the state can neither supply nor hinder.  <i>Pierce, supra</i>.  And
it is in recognition of this that these decisions have respected
the private realm of family life which the state cannot enter.
</blockquote><p>
In 1942, two years before <i>Prince</i>, the Court showed the enduring power
of the notion that the Constitution protects certain fundamental
relationships.  The case was <i>Skinner v. Oklahoma</i>,[12] and it struck
down a statute that authorized sterilization as a punishment for
a third conviction for certain crimes (a eugenics-era version
of &quot;three strikes and you're out&quot;).  The case was basically
resolved under the Equal Protection Clause of the 14th Amendment,
rather than the Due Process Clause, on the theory that Oklahoma
had made an irrational distinction in punishing some crimes by
sterilization while other, similar crimes were not subject to
such punishment.  But the driving force behind the ruling seems
to have been the Court's abhorrence of sterilization as a punishment,
and here the Court brought in the Due Process analysis familiar
from the <i>Meyer-Pierce</i> line of cases.
<p><blockquote>
We are dealing here with
legislation which involves one of the basic rights of man.  Marriage
and procreation are fundamental to the very existence and survival
of the race.[13]
</blockquote><p>
Notice that here, as in <i>Meyer</i> and <i>Pierce</i>, the Court
continues to see the protected right as inherently relational.
 It's &quot;marriage and procreation,&quot; neither of which are
solitary activities.  The Court is still protecting relationships,
rather than self-definition by isolated individuals.
<p>
Notice also that the Court has redefined the nature of the <i>Meyer-Pierce</i> 
holdings. It has given them a new lease on life in the post-1937 world
by ignoring their origins in economic substantive due process
and emphasizing instead their protection of the privacy of protected
relationships.
<p>
The next chapter in the development of the constitutional
privacy right was <i>Griswold v. Connecticut</i>[14] in 1965.  Here the Court
was faced with a very broad anti-contraceptive statute that it
very much wanted to strike down.  The problem was, how?  The Court
had long since rejected substantive due process, and, with it,
the notion that the Court is entitled to sit as a super-legislature,
striking down duly enacted statutes merely because it disagreed
with them.  Back in the 30's, liberals had thrown out the old
substantive due process that protected economic rights.  Would
the liberals of the 60's bring substantive due process back, so
as to protect privacy?
<p>
The answer was yes -- but they did it carefully.
 In a majority opinion by Justice Douglas, the Court in <i>Griswold</i>
reaffirmed the death of substantive due process and repudiated
the notion of legislating from the bench.[15]  It then looked for
constitution clauses other than the 14th Amendment Due Process
Clause for a way to strike down the statute.  What they came up
with was the theory that the 1st, 4th, and 5th Amendments all
protect privacy in some way;  plus, the 9th Amendment authorizes
judges to find new, non-textual rights;  so, on the whole, a general
right of privacy may be said to be one of the &quot;emanations&quot;
from &quot;penumbras&quot; of those amendments.[16]
<p>
The <i>Griswold</i> opinion has both a moderate face and a radical face.  Its moderate 
face is seen in the fact that the privacy right that it protected was
specifically a right of <i>marital</i> privacy.  The opinion contains
some glowing rhetoric about the importance and sacredness of the
marital relationship.[17] This rhetoric is fully consistent both
with the values of most Americans, and with the theory of relational
privacy as we have seen it in <i>Meyer</i> and <i>Pierce</i>, and both those
cases were among those cited in <i>Griswold</i>.[18]
<p>
The radical face of <i>Griswold</i> is seen in its headline value.  I have not 
looked up the original newspaper accounts of <i>Griswold</i>, but I feel reasonably 
confident that they did not say &quot;Court Affirms Privacy Doctrine,&quot;
or &quot;Court Embarks on New Substantive Due Process,&quot; or
&quot;Court Does Novel Analysis of 1st, 4th, 5th and 9th Amendments.&quot;
 No:  the real news value of <i>Griswold</i> lay in the fact that by
its effect, though not by its language, it elevated contraception
to the status of a constitutional right.  That elevation had profound
cultural impact.  Formerly, contraception was, no doubt, widely
practiced, but at the same time it lacked cultural cachet.  It
still carried connotations of the unrespectable, the bohemian.
<i>Griswold</i> had the effect of wrapping contraception in the red,
white, and blue; and, in so doing, it placed a certain judicial
seal of approval on the sexual revolution that was then in progress.
<p>
By 1972, the evidence suggested that this was precisely the direction
in which the Court intended to take the new substantive due process.
For instance, while <i>Griswold</i> seemed to create a due process right
to contraception only for married people, the Court in <i>Eisenstadt
v. Baird</i>[19] in 1972 used the Equal Protection Clause to extend the
same right to the unmarried.
<p>
It also completely contradicted the rhetoric in <i>Griswold</i> about marriage: 
whereas <i>Griswold</i> had cited the special, sacred nature of the marital 
relationship as a basis for finding a privacy right,[20] <i>Eisenstadt</i> heaped 
scorn on the notion that marriage is anything special, and affirmed instead
the continuing legal and metaphysical separateness of spouses.
<p>
Let's pause to retrace our steps.  We started in the 20's with <i>Meyer,
Bartels, Pierce</i>, and <i>Farrington</i>, which affirmed a right of privacy
for protected relationships, namely, those of the family.  They
made the family, especially in its role as bearer and rearer of
children, a zone of limited yet real legal autonomy.  We moved
on to <i>Skinner</i>, the sterilization case from 1942, where we saw
that the privacy doctrine had survived the death of substantive
due process and was still available to protect &quot;marriage
and procreation.&quot;  Then we saw <i>Griswold</i>, where procreation
drops out of the picture, and finally, <i>Eisenstadt</i>, where marriage
drops out of the picture.  The privacy right has by this point
become a constitutional right to reject the values that it was
originally designed to protect.
<p>
After <i>Eisenstadt</i>, the stage was set for <i>Roe v. Wade</i>.[21] 
Roe is probably the most analyzed case in legal history, and I'm certainly 
not going to break any new ground under it today.  In terms of the issues 
we're discussing today, there are two remarkable things about <i>Roe</i>.  One is 
that it dropped the pretense, maintained in <i>Griswold</i>, that the Court 
was doing something other than bringing back substantive due process, in
a new form and at the service of a different set of values.  Two,
it marked the final repudiation of the old relational approach
to privacy, where privacy protected relationships, and inaugurated
an era in which privacy stands for a sort of erotic hyper-individualism:
 an individual's right to define him- or herself, especially through
sexual activity, free from all binding commitments, and free from
all encumbrances other than those that the individual freely and
continuously chooses.
<p>
This is really the constitutionalization of the metaphysics of Jean-Paul Sartre 
and the Existentialists, who taught that the human person makes himself through 
his own choices.[22] It follows that choosing is more important than being,
and freedom is &quot;a constantly renewed obligation to remake
the <i>Self</i>....&quot;[23]
<p>
Although <i>Roe</i> contained a few hedges against this isolationist view of 
individualism -- where it says, for instance, that the woman &quot;cannot be 
isolated in her privacy&quot;[24] -- nonetheless, the later abortion cases 
entrenched isolationist individualism further into the Court's evolving 
concept of privacy. For instance, in <i>Planned Parenthood v. Danforth</i>[25] 
in 1975, the Court struck down a paternal consent requirement for abortion.
 The mutation of the privacy doctrine ought not to pass unnoticed.
 In <i>Meyer</i> and <i>Pierce</i>, it envisioned the parents, as a unit, 
exercising autonomy for the benefit of the child.  By the time we get to
<i>Danforth</i>, we find that it nullifies one parent's rights altogether,
and protects the other parent's autonomy at the expense of the
child.  Another way to look at the matter is that in the 20's,
the privacy right protected the family as such, while in the 70's,
it viewed family ties as one of the chief obstacles to privacy.
<p>
To be sure, the Court has not thrown itself four-square behind the
new view of privacy -- privacy as the individual's right, in isolation
from family and society, to define himself through an ongoing
process of choosing.  If it had, <i>Bowers v. Hardwick</i>[26] would have
come out the other way.  We know this because we have Justice
Blackmun's dissent in that case, which reads like a majority opinion,
which it very nearly was.
<p>
The dissenters in that case, not the majority, had a theory of human freedom, 
albeit one against which many objections could be raised.  The majority simply took 
the position that theories of freedom are one thing, constitutional
law is another, and nothing in the Constitution authorizes the
Court to act as the nation's official philosophy board.  That's
a very strong argument -- but, in a sense, much less interesting
than what the dissenters had to say.
<p>
The Blackmun dissent argued for a broad privacy doctrine while completely and 
explicitly rejecting the <i>Meyer-Pierce</i> view of privacy.  Wrote Justice 
Blackmun: &quot;We protect those rights [referring to marriage and family] not 
because they contribute, in some direct and material way, to the general
public welfare, but because they form so central a part of an
individual's life.&quot;[27]
<p>
For comparison, consider the key statement of the meaning of the privacy doctrine in 
<i>Pierce</i>. Justice McReynolds wrote for the Court:
<p>
<blockquote>The fundamental theory of liberty upon which
all governments in this Union repose excludes any general power
of the State to standardize its children by forcing them to accept
instruction from public teachers only.  The child is not the mere
creature of the State;  those who nurture him and direct his destiny
have the right, coupled with the high duty, to recognize and prepare
him for additional obligations.[28]
</blockquote><p>
The views of privacy endorsed by the Court in the 1920's, and those that it 
sometimes endorsed in the 1970's, are not absolutely contradictory, but they 
certainly pull in different directions.  Justice McReynolds could, theoretically,
have defended parents' rights in terms of the parents' individual
self-definitions, with their children being mere tools in the
parents' life projects.  Such a view would have been a perfect
fit with that of Blackmun in <i>Bowers</i>.   But instead, McReynolds
coupled parents' rights with parents' duties, and specifically
held that this package of rights and duties is oriented towards
preparing the child &quot;for additional obligations.&quot;  He
does not specify what those obligations are, but, from the very
fact that he views these terms as self-explanatory, we may infer
that he means the ordinary obligations of life in a democratic
republic:  being a good friend and neighbor, participating in
civic life, pulling one's own weight economically, taking care
of one's family, and so forth.[29]
<p>
For the mindset of the 1970's, on the other hand, all those obligations -- the 
claims of family, neighborhood, the political community, etc. -- are just so many
encumbrances on the free choice of the individual.  These two
human prototypes -- 1920's Man and 1970's Man, McReynolds Man
and Blackmun Man -- have barely enough in common even to speak
to each other.  From the point of view of 70's Man, 20's Man is
a bundle of complexes and prejudices who never has any fun.  From
the point of view of 20's Man, 70's Man is rootless and shallow,
a passive consumer of pleasurable sensations, not the sort of
person around whom any real community can be built.
<p>
It cannot be stressed too often, however, that constitutional law does not
necessarily force us to choose between 20's Man and 70's Man as
our preferred human type.  There is always the possibility that
the 14th Amendment does not incorporate either as its preferred
model for human society, but instead leaves that choice up to
the democratic process in the several states, cheerfully anticipating
that some states and localities will go in more of a 20's direction,
and others will go in more of a 70's direction.  This option is
the only one I know of that stands a chance of bringing peace
to our judicial politics.
<p>
As it happens, this option was also the
very one offered by Robert Bork.  Critical of the reasoning of
<i>Meyer</i> and <i>Pierce</i> no less than of that of Roe, his philosophy of
sticking narrowly to the constitutional text may have offered
the closest approximation to a truce in the wars over what kind
of privacy, what kind of human person, what kind of society is
envisioned in the 14th Amendment.  The story of his confirmation
battle is the story of how the partisans of 20's Man were willing
to accept this truce, but the partisans of 70's Man were not.
 The truce was rejected; the wars go on, judicially as well as
culturally.
<p>
Today it is simply a given, in the courts and in the
law reviews, that the Constitution protects privacy, <i>in some sense.</i>
 What sense precisely, future cases will have to tell.  The 90's
are not the 20's, but neither are they the 70's.
<p>
<center>***</center>
<p>
<i>David M. Wagner, Esq., is Director of Legal Policy at the Family Research
Council, a Washington, DC-based research and advocacy organization.</i>
<p><hr><p>
