<title>HEARING ON RELIGIOUS LIBERTY</title>
<body>
<center><img src="/townhall/FRC/podium/podium.gif">
<h2>HEARING ON RELIGIOUS LIBERTY</h2>
<h4>Testimony of Cathleen A. Cleaver, Esq.<br>
Director of Legal Studies, Family Research Council<br>
before the<br>
Committee on the Judiciary<br>
of the<br>
United States Senate<br>
October 25, 1995</h4></center>
<p><hr size=3 width=50%><p>
Mr. Chairman and Members of the Committee, I am the Director of
Legal Studies for the Family Research Council, a non-profit research
and advocacy organization, established to defend family, faith,
and freedom.  On behalf of Gary Bauer and the Family Research
Council, I want to express our sincere appreciation for the opportunity
to address this distinguished Committee on the critical issue
of religious liberty.
<p>
The First Amendment is not internally inconsistent.  The Establishment
Clause[1] was designed to prevent the State from coercing a religious
belief. The Free Exercise Clause[2] was designed to prevent the
State from interfering with the exercise of religious beliefs.
Thus, the religion clauses were designed to work hand-in-hand
to promote government neutrality with regard to religion.
<p>
In the last several decades, however, the Supreme Court has wrongly
interpreted the clauses to be antagonistic to each other.  The
Court has created a false conflict between the religion clauses
which must be reconciled in each case, and the Establishment Clause
prohibition has been the usual victor.  &quot;The government cannot
avoid aiding religion unless it actively opposes religion,&quot;
the argument goes.  More often than not, discrimination against
citizens or groups with religious viewpoints has become the only
constitutionally &quot;safe&quot; resolution to this false conflict.
Insistence on avoiding appearances of endorsement of or incidental
aid to religion has worked to inhibit the free exercise of religion.
Complementary clauses read to be inconsistent could not but 
result in inconsistent rulings.  The current &quot;chaos&quot;
in the federal courts in this area, therefore, is distressing,
but not surprising.
<p>
On October 20th, this Committee heard testimony from a distinguished
panel of experts who discussed the history of interpretation errors
in First Amendment religion clause jurisprudence, and efforts
to correct those errors by various federal statutes.  I will not
repeat this testimony, nor will I refute the argument that nothing
need be done, for the acceptability of that position is increasingly
waning.[3]
<p>
I will, instead, attempt to explain our preference for a constitutional
amendment rather than a federal statute, and address specific
concerns which have been raised in the public debate. 
<p>
The Family Research Council supports an amendment to the constitution
clarifying the First Amendment's prohibition of discrimination
against religious expression, and against persons, groups, or
organizations in access to government benefits or protections
on account of the religious character of their speech or identity.
We do not favor changing the First Amendment in any way.  Rather,
we support an amendment which would correct the Supreme Court's
misinterpretation of the First Amendment.
<p>
Several concerns and questions have been raised about the amendment
approach and its ramifications.
<p>
<B>1. Is such a radical approach really necessary?</B>  First,
it is wise to keep from confusing <I>procedure</I> with <I>substance.</I>
Amending the constitution is a radical procedure, to be sure.
Article V of the Constitution ensures that it is not to be achieved
without effort and consensus.  Yet, the substance of a restorative
religious liberty amendment need not be radical in nature.  Legal
experts and numerous interested groups have examined potential
approaches for months, and the Family Research Council remains
willing to continue to discuss specific language for the amendment.
We are especially eager to hear your specific ideas, Mr. Chairman,
and those of Congressman Hyde. For purposes of discussion this
morning, I will center my comments on the draft proposal garnering
considerable support, and presented to this Committee at the October
20th hearing:[4]
<p><blockquote>
<b>In order to secure the unalienable right of the people to
acknowledge, worship, and serve their Creator, neither the United
States nor any State shall deny benefits to or otherwise discriminate
against any persons, acting in a private capacity, on account
of their religious expression, belief, or identity; and the exercise
by such persons of freedom of religion, speech, press, or association
shall not be construed as an establishment of religion.</b>
</blockquote><p>
This language would, in effect, say to government, &quot;do not
discriminate against persons on account of their religious beliefs,&quot;
and to the Supreme Court, &quot;do not construe this non-discriminatory
treatment to be a governmental establishment of religion.&quot;
The fact that some civil liberties groups call the Amendment
extreme does not make it so.  It is a negative mandate upon government:
do not discriminate and do not misconstrue.  It bestows no new
rights, it apportions no new responsibilities.  Far from &quot;injecting
the federal government into the situation&quot; as some critics
perceive, the Religious Liberty Amendment  protects religious
liberty by ensuring government neutrality toward religion.  The
Amendment is not radical in substance.  Indeed, it is nothing
more than an embodiment of First Amendment principles properly
understood.
<p>
<B>2.  If it is not radical, why is it necessary?</B>  It is necessary
to correct serious misinterpretations of a Constitution provision.
 It is restorative, not creative.  The amendment process is an
appropriate means of clarifying the Constitution of the People.
Several constitutional amendments have been in the nature of clarifications,
especially the voting rights amendments.
<p>
<B>3.  Some suggest that the Court is coming around on its own,
obviating the need for an amendment</B>. <i>Rosenberger v. University
of Virginia</i> is generally cited here.[5] <i>Rosenberger</i>,
however, like other 5-4 decisions with multiple opinions, is a
very fact-dependent decision.  In reversing the University of
Virginia's decision to withhold student activity funds for a Christian
student magazine, Justice Kennedy found it important that Wide
Awake Productions, the publisher, was not a &quot;religious organization&quot;
and that the funds would go to a printing company rather than
directly to the student publication.[6] Moreover, Justice O'Connor
warned in her concurrence that <i>Rosenberger</i> is not meant
to establish any bright-line test.[7] Despite its disclaimers and
reservations, <i>Rosenberger</i> was a good result, yet there
is simply no reason to conclude that <i>Rosenberger</i> signals
a new consistency in religion clause jurisprudence.  Indeed, Justice
Souter in his dissent went so far as to say that neutrality toward
religion is not required by the First Amendment.  It could be
years before another religious discrimination case of this kind
is taken up by the high court.  In the meantime, some Americans'
precious First Amendment rights are held in abeyance, the deprivation
of which is an irreparable harm.
<p>
<B>4.  Will a Religious Liberty Amendment prevent any future misconstruction
of the Religion Clauses?</B>  No.  And it is, of course,  possible
that the Amendment itself will be misconstrued.  Any assertion
to the contrary would be disingenuous.  But to concede these points
does not then force a concession that the Amendment will be futile
or meaningless.  The Supreme Court made a wrong turn in 1947 in
<i>Everson v. Board of Education</i>;[8] momentum and the weighty principle of 
<I>stare decisis</I>[9] have worked against the Court's righting itself.
Even considering the possibility of misinterpretation, an amendment
would dislodge the Court from its faulty construction of internal
inconsistency in the First Amendment.
<p>
<B>5. Will the Amendment create a new entitlement program for
church-related programs or schools?</B>  No. Government has no
obligation to provide funds to private schools, for example. 
Yet, if government should decide to do so, a Religious Liberty
Amendment would prevent the government from discriminating in
favor of private secular schools and against private parochial
schools.[10] The Amendment would <I>permit</I> government to fund
secular classes in religious schools, but would not <I>require</I>
government to fund such classes.   Religious activities would
not be funded by the government -- the Amendment would not eradicate
the Establishment Clause, after all -- but activities conducted
in religious settings or by religious people could be funded,
if such activities were within the purview of the secular government
funding program.  The &quot;pervasively sectarian&quot; or &quot;pervasively
religious&quot; analysis would be abandoned.
<p>
<B>6. Would an Amendment allow teacher-led prayer?</B> No. 
The Amendment would ensure that persons in their private capacity
would be free from discrimination, but government employees, including
teachers, would be subject to the restrictions of the Establishment
Clause when acting in their official capacity, such as when teaching.
<p>
<B>7. Why not seek a statutory remedy?</B>  A federal statute
could ultimately be futile.  While such a statute would initially
resolve inconsistencies from state to state,[11] the Supreme Court
would remain the final arbiter of the Constitution.  A federal
statute would not prevent judges from continuing to misconstrue
the First Amendment.  While a statute might survive a facial challenge,
an &quot;as applied&quot; challenge would quite possibly be adjudged
unconstitutional under current precedent.  A statutory &quot;solution&quot;
would be a hollow victory, if, at the end of the day, the substantial
efforts to draft, enact, and defend a statute were swiftly abolished
by one Supreme Court opinion.  When the roof is leaking, repair
the roof -- don't buy more buckets.
<p>
The Religious Liberty Amendment could be thought of as the religious
&quot;neutrality&quot; amendment.  This principle of neutrality
is not new -- it is the aim and result of our First Amendment's
religion clauses properly understood.  A Religious Liberty Amendment
could restore this saving principle, so that our First Amendment
would not be used to promote the empty state religion of secularism, but to 
promote true freedom, and the prospect of freedom's fulfillment in truth, 
to which every American is entitled.
<p>
-- 10/25/95
<p>
<center>***</center>
<p>
<i>Cathleen A. Cleaver, Esq., is Director of Legal Studies at
the Family Research Council, a Washington, D.C.-based research
and advocacy organization.</i>
<p><hr><p>
