<html>
<title>HOW SOCIAL SECURITY AFFECTS THE TAX REFORM DEBATE</title>
<body>
<center><img src="/townhall/FRC/podium/podium.gif">
<h2>HOW SOCIAL SECURITY<br>
AFFECTS THE TAX REFORM<br>
DEBATE</h2>
<p><hr size=3 width=50%><p>
<i>by<br>
William R. Mattox, Jr.</center>
<p>
This speech was given at the Heritage Foundation Resource Bank
Meeting on April 27, 1995 in Philadelphia, Pa.</i>
<p>
This morning's topic is going on the offensive and in thinking
about the range of ideas one could talk about, I was struck by
how many opportunities we now have before us -- and how many of
these ideas would not have even been worthy of discussion just
a short time ago.
<p>
Indeed, today everything is on the table -- except Social Security,
which is why I'd like to devote most of my remarks this morning
to Social Security.  Now, I'm not going to advance any new ideas
about Social Security reform.  I'm not even going to talk about
Social Security directly.
<p>
Instead, I'm going to talk about why anti-family biases inherent
in the Social Security system <b>must</b> be taken into consideration
when we seek to legislate in other areas -- most especially in
pursuing a conservative tax cut agenda.  As you know, the House
recently passed the American Dream Restoration Act -- the crown
jewel of the Contract with America.
<p>
The centerpiece of this measure is a $500 tax credit for children.
Within the conservative movement, there are three views of this
pro-family tax cut:
<p>
1. <b>Social issues conservatives</b> love it and often make
a case for it by citing the extraordinary erosion in per-child
tax benefits since 1950.
<p>
2. <b>Deficit hawks</b> hate it.  They perceive it to be a revenue
drain and claim Americans don't want tax cuts as much as they
want deficit reduction.  This is a questionable proposition, but
even if true, there is nothing that says you can't do both.
<p>
3. <b>Supply-siders</b> are torn about pro-family tax relief.
 On the one hand, most agree with Milton Friedman who says he
has never seen a tax cut he didn't like; and most appreciate the
political argument that pro-family tax relief can enhance the chances 
of passing capital gains cuts and cuts in spending programs.  On the 
other hand, most supply siders see no short-term payoff in terms of 
economic growth -- and for this reason, many want to do the least 
amount necessary to secure pro-family votes.
<p>
Now, I share the supply-siders' interest in growth, but I believe
there is a very compelling economic argument for making pro-family tax relief
our top tax-cut priority.  Allan Carlson of the Rockford Institute
has argued that the Social Security system robs parents of the
social insurance value of their children.  That is, if there were
no old-age social insurance scheme, adults in our society would
have an economic incentive to invest a portion of their time and
money in the rearing of children in order to protect themselves
against the prospect of being destitute in old age.
<p>
Now, Carlson is not suggesting that childrearing is the only means
of protecting oneself against poverty in old age.  Certainly,
one can and should save for such purposes.  Nor is Carlson suggesting
that this economic incentive is, or ever should be, the primary
motivation for raising children.  Certainly, moral imperatives
are, or should be, far more significant factors.  But Carlson
believes moral principles and economic forces should work in harmony.
Yet, in our current system, moral and economic forces are in
conflict.  In our current system, it is economically foolish to
invest in childrearing, for under Social Security productive adults
can live it up today on the resources that might otherwise be
diverted to childrearing and live it up tomorrow on the resources
Social Security takes from other people's adult children and gives
to them.
<p>
This bias calls for fundamental reform of the Social Security
system.  But if such reform cannot even be discussed, then it
is incumbent upon us to offset these anti-family effects through
some other means -- the most logical being per-child tax savings.
 How much in per-child tax savings would be necessary to neutralize
the Social Security system's anti-child bias?  By my calculations,
$2,100 -- and I'll be happy to explain later how I arrived at
that figure if anyone wants to know.
<p>
When one considers that most children offer their parents less
than $400 in tax savings, you can appreciate why some of us pro-family
yahoos hardly regard $500 in addition tax savings as excessive.
Not only does Social Security indirectly discourage people from
having children, but it indirectly discourages them from raising
kids well.  Indeed, under the current system, workaholics who
neglect their childrearing responsibilities do not stand to suffer
economically if their kids grow up to be dolts or sloths (so long
as everybody else's kids can produce enough to keep the
Social Security system afloat).  But in a natural economy free
of old-age entitlements, neglectful parents would stand to lose
much.
<p>
To offset Social Security's bias against investments of parental
time and attention, Carlson argues that we not only need an income
tax -- but a progressive one at that.  A progressive income tax,
he argues, has the effect of causing parents at some point to
shift their attention from paid work to the unpaid work of raising children.
Now, I have little reason to believe that Carlson's enthusiasm
for a progressive income tax is widely shared by many here.
<p>
But lest one think his view represents a threat to the <b>adoption</b>
of a flat tax, it should be noted that, for all practical purposes,
we already have a flat tax.  That's right, when one <b>combines</b>
current income tax rates with current Social Security tax rates,
nearly all taxpayers have a marginal tax rate of roughly 30 percent.
Crudely speaking, for those making below $60,000, this rate is
divided almost equally between a 15 percent income tax rate and
a 15 percent payroll tax.  For most of those making over $60,000,
this 30 percent is derived from a 28 percent income tax rate and
a 2 percent Medicare tax.  While this is a reality that all of
the leading &quot;flat tax&quot; plans currently ignore, it is
a reality that need not threaten many of the appealing features
of such plans -- features like eliminating tax withholding, simplifying
tax forms, and getting rid of many tax write-offs and deductions.
<p>
One tax deduction that ought not to be scrapped, however, is the
charitable deduction.  From the standpoint of economic theory,
I do not know whether there is a compelling reason for preserving
the charitable deduction.  I suspect there is -- but it really
doesn't matter, because the short-run political argument for preserving
the charitable tax deduction is so powerful that no other argument
is perhaps necessary.  If one of our major goals is, as it should
be, dismantling the welfare state, then I think we should recognize
that few Americans are likely to view as credible any agenda which
simultaneously seeks to gut public housing and to eliminate tax
incentives for giving to Habitat for Humanity.  If you think the
public drubbing conservatives took on school lunch was bad, wait
until you see what the Left would do with that.
<p>
Unless we are more troubled by charitable tax deductions than
AFDC and public housing, I think we should steer clear of any
tax simplification plan that eliminates charitable contributions.
Indeed, if we truly want to dismantle the welfare state, I think
we ought to be looking at ways to expand charitable deductions
to non-itemizers as well as ways to permit taxpayers to divert
a portion of their tax liability to a charitable cause of their
choosing.
<p>
Having devoted most of my speech to the indirect effect of Social
Security on various tax issues, I want to close my remarks by
talking about restoring the social institution that provides greater
security -- yes, greater social security -- than any other.  It's
the institution of marriage.  And it is in serious shape.
<p>
My friends, no proactive idea being talked about at this conference
is likely to prevent the eventual collapse of our civilization
unless we see a restoration of lifelong marriage.  While the factors
influencing family breakdown are primarily moral or cultural,
there are at least a few policy ideas worth exploring in these
arenas.
<p>
<i>At the state and local level, we need to be:</i>
<ul><p>
<li>Advancing divorce reform initiatives which require fault to
be established in cases where one spouse wishes to contest the
divorce.  (Current law now favors the spouse wanting to leave
the marriage rather than the one wishing to save the marriage.)
<p>
<li>Advancing tough anti-illegitimacy measures in the context
of welfare reform.
<p>
<li>Promoting abstinence-based programs in schools where sex education
is taught.
<p></ul>
<i>At the federal level we need to:</i>
<ul><p>
<li>Eliminate the Legal Services Corporation, which finances some
300,000 divorces a year.
<p>
<li>Address the perplexing problem of the tax treatment of marriage
in a manner that helps all married couples -- perhaps with a tax
provision tied not just to marital status, but to marital length.
 By extending larger tax benefits with each year a couple stays
together, the tax code could pass along the societal savings of
marital stability to those who have avoided divorce the longest.
</ul><p>
While it is important for us to recognize the virtues of these
pro-family policy reforms, it is also important for us to recognize
the limitations of all policy instruments.  Pro-family tax relief,
for example, will not make husbands love their wives or children
respect their parents.  It will not clean up filthy T.V. or remove
child predators from our streets.  Pro-family tax relief will
not, by itself, magically solve the various social problems facing
America's families, neighborhoods and communities.
<p>
But pro-family tax relief will make it easier for families to
thrive by reducing economic stress.  It will make it easier for
parents to monitor their children's T.V. viewing habits by freeing
them to spend more time with their children.  It will empower
parents to address many family needs that only they can meet.
<p>
This is why pro-family tax relief is so critical -- and why all
parts of the conservative movement ought to embrace it enthusiastically.
<p>
-- 11/8/95
<p>
<center>***</center>
<p>
<i>William R. Mattox, Jr. is vice president for policy at the
Family Research Council in Washington, D.C.</i>

<p>

