<html>
<title>EFFECTIVE COMPASSION</title>
<body>
<center><img src="/townhall/FRC/podium/podium.gif">
<h2>EFFECTIVE COMPASSION</h2>
<p><hr size=3 width=50%><p>
<i>by<br>
Dr. Marvin Olasky</i></center>
<p>
<i>This speech was presented at the Family Research Council's
&quot;World Without Welfare&quot; symposium on December 13, 1995
at the Willard Hotel in Washington, D.C.</i>
<p>
This is somewhat of a difficult assignment for me.  At this point,
the only time I get nervous in speaking is when my wife is in
the room.  My goal in life is to try to please her, and I start
to wonder and worry.  As I look around the room here today, I
see not my wife -- she is happily warm in Texas -- but so many
other people from whom I've learned so much and whom I honor.
John Perkins over here, who has been doing wonderful things for
30 years.  Wayne Gordon with the Christian Community Development
Association.  Guy Condon with Care Net.  Duane Higgins in Alabama.
Reverend Ron Moore in Mississippi.  Father Sirico of the Acton
Institute in Michigan.  Bill Schambra from the Bradley Foundation.
Reverend John Woods and Mrs. Woods from the Gospel Mission here
in Washington.  I was noting down the people as I came in the
room.  It just goes on and on.
<p>
So what can I possibly do to explain what's going on to all these
folks from whom I've learned so much?  Just a few thoughts.  And
this may not be the best-organized speech you will have heard
this year, but it comes from the heart.
<p>
<center><h3>WELFARE: THE THIRD CHARGE</h3></center>
<p>
I start out by thinking about all the people here who are not
only well-intentioned but also intent on seeing good results,
who understand the difference between effective compassion and
what is well-intentioned but often does exactly the opposite of
what it sets out to do.  I have found in traveling around the
country this year lots and lots of soft hearts, wonderfully soft
hearts.  But, alas, they tend to go along with soft heads.  You
see this in church bulletins with notices about helping the homeless.
Here are three that have been brought to my attention this year.
First, &quot;Thursday night:  dinner for the homeless.  Medication
to follow.&quot;  Here's another, &quot;At the evening service
tonight the sermon topic will be 'Seeing Hell Close Up.'  Come
early to meet homeless visitors.&quot;  And one more, &quot;Don't
let homelessness kill you.  Let the church help.&quot;  A lot
of good intentions, a lot of soft hearts, some soft heads as well.
<p>
This is a wonderful hotel to be meeting in.  This is the hotel
where U.S. Grant used to hang out when he came here right after
the Civil War -- or as we call it in Texas still, the &quot;War
of Northern Aggression.&quot;  U.S. Grant, when he stayed here
following the Civil War, did not have much of a sense of humor.
But you could excuse him for that.  He had seen too much during
that terrible war in which 600,000 soldiers died.  Recently I
visited the Cold Harbor Battlefield southeast of Richmond.  That's
the one where Grant ordered three frontal assaults against strong
Confederate positions.  It was obvious to the soldiers that they
could not make it.  It was so obvious that they sewed their names
and addresses to the backs of their uniforms before the battle
so that their bodies could be identified and the next of kin notified
more easily.  Grant later said that his biggest regret of the
whole war was ordering that third charge.  The first, maybe, just
to see whether it could be done.  The second, dubious.  The third,
just a total tragic disaster.  The body count just went on and
on.  People stacked up in an area the length of about a football
field and the width of maybe a couple of fields.
<p>
At least U.S. Grant admitted that he had made a mistake.  And
that is far more than some liberal defenders of the welfare status
quo are now doing.  The <I>Washington Post</I> yesterday had a
headline, &quot;Daschle Says Final Welfare Plan Has Lost Democratic
Support.&quot;  And so all that's left apparently is to defend
the status quo.  That should be an oxymoron:  a liberal defender
of the status quo.  That's a combination that is not quite right,
like &quot;dry rain&quot; or &quot;trustworthy Clinton.&quot;
But alas, the liberals who come from such a proud tradition of
looking at the horizon, going where no man has gone before (or
at least sometimes no sane man), are now left with defending the
status quo.  Liberals, with this wonderful tradition of so much
progress, particularly in racial matters, are defending the status
quo.  How the mighty have fallen.
<p>
It's even worse.  We saw through the 1970s and the 1980s how children
suffered as families dissolved or never were formed by people
who had the consciousness of the sixties.  Some had soft hearts,
but many had soft heads.  And now in the '90s, the last refuge
of liberalism with its great tradition is to defend the status
quo and to push forward the children again as hostages.  The body
count of those children over the last 30 years is enormous.  They're
stacked up like soldiers were at Cold Harbor.  But liberals' last
refuge is to go at it again.  It is a third charge at Cold Harbor,
and at least the folks who defend the status quo could have the
decency to sew the name tags on the backs of those children.
<p>
<center><h3>THE COMPASSION DEFICIT</h3></center>
<p>
As you can see, I'm not fond of what passes for the Democratic
position these days.  But I can give only one or two cheers for
the Republican position because conservatives have not really
taken advantage so far of the opportunities to replace welfare
that have been created by the failure of liberalism.  Many conservatives
are still content to be the party of hardheadedness and, in perception
and sometimes reality, hardheartedness as well.  They tend to
say, &quot;Okay, we're hard.  We have hard heads.  Maybe we have
hard hearts, but you folks on the other side have soft heads and
soft hearts, and when it comes right down to it the voters will
prefer hard-hard to soft-soft.&quot;  Well, maybe they're right
politically.  I tend to think not.  I don't think they'll be successful
in retaining public confidence long enough to really end the budget
deficit if they do not deal with the compassion deficit.  And
that's something the Republicans have not really dealt with yet
for the most part.  Maybe they can get away with it politically,
hard-hard versus soft-soft, but what's right and what the American
people want are folks who are warmhearted but tough-minded.  People
want that combination, and so far neither party has really been
producing it as its main position.  And so, conservatives need
to realize that cost is not the main reason at all to fight governmental
welfare programs.  It's a factor certainly.  It becomes a huge
tax burden for middle-class taxpayers, for example.  But the real
fundamental problem is that we're too stingy in what's truly important:
treating people as human beings made in God's image, not as animals
to be fed, caged and occasionally petted.
<p>
The real need is for leaders who are tough-minded, but also tenderhearted.
And willing to recognize the creation of people in God's image
and the need to treat people that way -- not just looking at it
through green eyeshades as a budgetary matter.  There are some
conservatives who've realized that.  There are some who understand
that.  Newt Gingrich does.  He's getting terrible press these
days.  He's gotten hard press all year, but he understands this.
Bill Bennett understands this.  There are some senators -- Dan
Coats, John Ashcroft, Rick Santorum -- who understand this.  There
are some members of Congress, and some governors I've met in my
travels around the country this year: George Allen, Kirk Fordice,
Fife Symington, and John Engler.  I think they have a sense of
this, and it's starting to come out in the way they speak.  It's
starting to come out in the types of legislation that they may
be moving through their states.  The critical understanding here
is that private programs that are challenging, personal, and spiritual
can do a better job than these failed governmental programs and
that people who are really concerned with helping the poor and
protecting children should not be doing any more to defend this
failed status quo.
<p>
Until that becomes the common understanding and message, until
liberals are ready to move away from the status quo, until conservatives
are ready to understand that it's not primarily a budgetary matter
-- that it's a matter of dreams and not just dollars -- then poor
people will stay on the welfare plantation and folks who want
to misuse the word &quot;compassion&quot; to derive political
capital will still get away with it.  At this point, it's hard
to say what's going to happen with this year's welfare bill. 
It may go down.  It's hard to predict from one moment to the next
what President Clinton will do.  I'm not sure he himself knows.
And so there's a lot of bad news these days.  But when you get
around the country, outside Washington, there's absolutely no
reason to be in social or political despair.  Why?  Because both
history and the present-day efforts represented by many people
here in this room show us the alternative to either softheadedness
or hardheartedness.  And that's what I want to emphasize right
now: the positive alternatives.  There is a way that good things
can come out of this year's effort, despite the failure of both
political parties to approach the question adequately.
<p>
<center><h3>UNDERSTANDING HISTORY</h3></center>
<p>
Let me just mention quickly the history.  After all, the reason
I'm speaking to you today is because I spent a year in the bowels
of the Library of Congress searching through old records.  I became
a witness to what the predecessors of many folks here in this
room, striving so diligently, accomplished.  I can testify to
all these folks whom the standard history books have forgotten.
And if you had history courses in high school or college, I suspect
that you've never heard of some of these people whom I'll refer
to today.  And there are lots more who are great heroes of faith
in practice.
<p>
Men like Charles Brace.  Here's a guy who over a 40-year period,
from 1850 to 1890, built lodging homes in New York City that provided
shelter to several hundred thousand abandoned children.  Over
the years, he placed 91,000 children in adoptive homes.  This
was his life.  This was his career.  This was his calling, and
he performed it wonderfully.
<p>
Women like Helen Mercy Woods.  From 1881 to 1903, she ran a shelter
in Chicago for pregnant and unmarried women.  Month after month
she gave personal attention to each newcomer.  She rejoiced as
their babies were born.  She helped some of her charges get married,
others to place their children for adoption, some to get jobs.
She kept at it year after year, as many people in this room have
kept at it year after year.
<p>
I can testify about some other forgotten heroes and heroines.
Annie Richardson Kennedy.  She ran a home for unwed moms in New
York City between 1900 and 1920.  Her goal was, first, to bring
the girls in touch with their Savior and then to build character.
She provided love and opportunity for thousands, and then she
disappeared into the fog of history.  My wife doesn't mind when
I fall in love with women like Helen Mercy Woods or Annie Richardson
Kennedy.  They've all been dead for a long time.  The text books
are silent.  They've been forgotten, and I want to testify to
the contributions they made.
<p>
They're part of a larger story that none of us learned about in
high school or college.  During the 19th century, before the federal
government ever got involved, there was a war on poverty that
was far, far more successful than our own -- especially considering
the degree of difficulty they had, considering that America was
a much poorer nation a hundred years ago than it is today.  It
was a war waged by tens of thousands of local, private charitable
agencies and religious groups around the country.  It was successful,
not because they abolished poverty, but because they witnessed
movement out of poverty by millions of people.  It was successful
because there were springs of fresh water flowing among the poor,
not just blocks of ice sitting in a perpetual winter of multi-generational
welfare dependency, always winter and never Christmas.  It was
successful because the optimism that was prevalent then contrasts
so sharply with the demoralization among the poor and the cynicism
among the better off that's so common now.  I can testify that
there was a great cloud of witnesses to effective poverty-fighting.
They succeeded in large ways by knowing and doing small but vital
things.
<p>
They knew first of all that the literal meaning of &quot;compassion&quot;
is not just writing a check, but having personal involvement with
the needy -- &quot;suffering with them.&quot;  That's what &quot;compassion&quot;
means: suffering with people, not just giving to them.  The poverty-fighters
of old knew that welfare doesn't mean passing a bill, but helping
a person to fare well.  These are some simple, elementary things
that our legislators seem to have forgotten.  The older generation
knew that people should be challenged.  When an able-bodied man
came to a homeless shelter, for example, he often was asked to
chop wood for an hour or two.  Or maybe whitewash the wall of
a building.  That way he could provide part of his own support
and also help those unable to chop.  They knew.  They demonstrated
through those work tests that even the most run-down person is
not just a taker.  He can also be a giver.  They knew that everyone
is made in God's image and is capable of helping.  Why have so
many people forgotten that?  Well, we don't know much about history.
<p>
History has taught us what to avoid.  Those poverty-fighters warned
us.  I'll give you just a few of their warnings, amazingly prophetic.
Mary Richmond, one of my heroines from the Baltimore Charity
Organizing Society in 1897:  &quot;Relief given without reference
to friends and neighbors is accompanied by moral loss.  Poor neighborhoods
are doomed to grow poorer whenever the natural ties of neighborliness
are weakened by well-meant but unintelligent interference.&quot;
<p>
Carl Herrick is here from the Daylight Foundation in Louisiana,
trying to get some good stuff going there.  Well, the New Orleans
Charity Organization Society in 1899 wisely noted that  &quot;intelligent
giving and intelligent withholding are alike to charity.  Giving
money to a poor person by itself is morally neutral.  The action
can hurt if not done wisely.  If done well with discernment, it's
the best thing in the world.  If done poorly, you're only helping
a person continue on the path of destruction.&quot;
<p>
And New York charity leader Josephine Lowell:  &quot;The problem
before those who'd be charitable is not how to deal with the given
number of the poor.  It's how to help those who are poor without
adding to their numbers and constantly increasing the evils they
seek to cure.&quot;
<p>
They were very forceful.  I'll give you one more quotation here:
&quot;It's important to reform those mild, well-meaning, tenderhearted,
sweet-voiced criminals who insist upon indulging in indiscriminate
charity.&quot;  Well, they were prophetic.  But we don't know
much about history.  We've forgotten America's past successes
in poverty-fighting, and the result has been the waste of not
just billions of dollars each year but the death of part of the
American dream.
<p>
<center><h3>THE CHALLENGE OF REAL COMPASSION</h3></center>
<p>
Now let me take a moment to mention this.  This is something that
some members of the Congress, I think, understand very well. 
But others need to just drop the green eye-shades and get into
real people, real lives, real dreams, and not just the dollars.
The critical part, the essential problem of the welfare system
now, is that sometimes it succeeds in keeping people fed.  But
it kills dreams.
<p>
It kills the helping dream of many Americans.  You know, most
of you, that millions of other people would like to be generous
at the entrance to the Metro here in Washington or at street corners
in your own towns.  But if you know, and there have been studies
showing this, that most homeless recipients will use any available
funds for drugs or alcohol, the tendency is to end up walking
by, avoiding eye contact.  And there's a subtle hardening that
occurs once more.
<p>
Welfare also kills the dreams of social workers.  A lot of conservatives
sometimes talk as if social workers are our enemies.  Not so at
all.  For the most part, these are extraordinarily well-intentioned
people.  The common lament they have is, &quot;All we have time
to do is move paper.&quot;  Here's a comment from a young social
worker who had the calling, who worked at it for a couple of years
and then just couldn't do it anymore.  He said, &quot;I had a
calling.  It was that simple.  I wanted to help.&quot;  And then
he resigned.  Frustrated and worn down, burned out, realizing
that he just wasn't doing any good.
<p>
And then there are some conservatives who talk as if the enemy
is poor individuals themselves.  Again, for the most part, not
so at all.  Welfare kills dreams among poor individuals who gradually
become used to dependency.  The worst thing for children is the
fatalism that often sets in.  And we've seen this, and there are
studies that show, that after a generation or especially two generations
of welfare there is a sense of, &quot;Whatever I do, it's not
going to do any good.  My mom was this way.  I'm going to be this
way.  Probably my children are going to be this way.&quot;  It
just goes on and on and on.  A fatalism.
<p>
Children need challenge.  Kids need a sense of opportunity.  They
don't get that in the welfare system.  And, in fact, they see
that adults who sacrifice leisure time and work hard to remain
independent are often called chumps rather than champs.  It kills
the dreams among children who grow up without fathers.  Those
of you who've coached a Little League team know this.  If there
were kids without fathers there, you knew.  You can tell who's
in that situation.  They alternately cling and show standoffishness
in a way that kids with functioning dads don't.  And it breaks
your heart.  So welfare kills.
<p>
A couple of weeks ago, I spent some time in south central Los
Angeles talking with some welfare moms there who told me about
-- here's an expression I didn't  know before -- 
&quot;county-check-pillow-pimps.&quot;
That's the expression they use.  Guys who come in on the last
day of the month.  They're called &quot;county checks&quot; because
in California you get the welfare check through the county.  Guys
come in on the last day of the month, they spend the night, they
get part of the welfare check that comes from the county the next
day.  So welfare has deprived kids of fathers, and it has deprived
women of husbands.  And I'm not saying that welfare is the cause,
but it certainly is an enabler.  Instead of helping to ennoble
people in poverty, helping them to fight, welfare tells people
to give in.  It enables them to stay in it.  And it kills.
<p>
Welfare packs a theological as well as a cultural punch.  After
all, how do children understand the nature of God the Father?
How do wives understand that Christ is the good husband for His
bride, the church, when they have no experience?  They've had
no experience at all with good fathers or good husbands, and they
don't know anyone who has in their whole block.
<p>
So Washington conservatives need to spend more time with folks,
poor people who are striving to get out of welfare.  If more people
actually walked the mean streets a little bit, they'd come to
understand this crucial point.  The reason to fight these governmental
welfare programs is not because they're too expensive, but because
they're inevitably too stingy in what is truly important: treating
people as human beings made in God's image, not as animals.
<p>
<center><h3>RECOVERING THE LOST TOOLS OF CHARITY</h3></center>
<p>
But again, no reason to despair.  There is good news around the
country.  Folks here in this room who are doing it know it.  We
are recovering the lost tools of charitable success.  We're seeing
a new great cloud of witnesses emerge.  We're living in an era
with many heroes, or, I should say, ordinary people who become
heroic as they show through hard &quot;suffering-with&quot; that
the American dream of compassion is not dead.  I don't know whether
John Perkins was heroic 30 years ago.  I've read his autobiography,
and I guess that he was heroic.  But he has grown in stature,
I suspect, over these years.  He has grown in grace and the knowledge
of our Lord and Savior, Jesus Christ.  You continue to grow and
develop.
<p>
There are other people I've met who, when they started out in
their ministries, were really folks you would not consider to
be charismatic individuals at all.  They've become so over the
years.  They've learned.  They've grown.  One example.  A friend
of mine now, Bob Cote in Denver.  He's a tall, white ex-boxer.
He spent a year on the streets as an alcoholic in the early '80s.
Then he pulled together a few of his fellow winos and junkies
to start a homeless shelter, a program in Denver that's known
as Step 13.  Bob showed me around his four-story building -- he'd
be glad to give you a tour if you're in Denver sometime.  He showed
me how mostly dead people from off the streets can step-by-step
come back to life.  They can get jobs with increasing responsibility.
They can get rooms within that building that gradually reflect
greater independence.  They go from a big dormitory, to kind of
an alcove, to separate rooms with a lock on the door.  And they're
buying their own furniture and getting their own phone accounts,
and they're ready to step out and lead independent, responsible
lives.  It's a tough, time-intensive process, but Bob Cote has
been there himself.  He's there to help others.
<p>
A person right here in Washington, Hannah Hawkins, who lives down
in Anacostia.  A great person to visit.  She's short, black and
retired, but she voluntarily runs an after-school program that
has several dozen children doing their homework, receiving the
love they often don't get at home.  You go down there and sometimes
it's wild.  Sometimes those kids run around like lost sheep, but
she knows each one of her lambs by name.  It's challenging, it's
personal, it's spiritual.
<p>
I wish you'd come with me and visit Freddy Garcia in San Antonio.
He's a softhearted but hardheaded Hispanic ex-addict.  He formed
Victory Outreach some 30 years ago in San Antonio to help substance
abusers.  Groups based on his teaching now have spread throughout
Texas to California, even as far south as Peru.  I've sat in his
home this year.  I've watched the way he patiently counsels and
teaches those whom everyone else has abandoned.
<p>
This has been a good year for me, with all the travel and hubbub
and so forth.  I've really been blessed to see and come to know
some of these people.  And I'm here to testify that they succeeded,
and they're still succeeding and others can too.  They have the
common understanding.  They picked it up somewhere, somehow, that
in order to be effective, compassion must be challenging, personal
and spiritual.  CPS for short.  Just like CPR can bring back to
life a dying person, CPS can bring back to life that dying American
dream.
<p>
Again, if you're not familiar with some of these places, go and
visit.  Go down about a mile away to Clean and Sober Streets here
in Washington or the Gospel Mission with Reverend Woods.  At Clean
and Sober Streets, it's interesting that there are really tough
rules just as there are at the Gospel Mission.  One strike, you're
out.  There is compassion that is challenging, personal, and spiritual
at the Right Alternative Center in Milwaukee.  This is something
that Bill Schambra from the Bradley Foundation knows about well,
and has helped quite a bit.  People sometimes say that AFDC moms
will be stuck on the government rolls for a lifetime.  You go
there and you talk with the folks, and you will learn that the
moms there take a 13-part pledge.  They pledge to change their
own behavior.  Not to swear, not to shack up, not to do drugs.
And the leaders there challenge them to stick to their pledges.
And when they do, their lives change.  Some of them get married,
some of them get jobs, they run their households better, their
kids start doing better in school, the kids break out of their
fatalism.  That's the key enemy: not poverty, but fatalism.
<p>
There's compassion of that sort at the Union Gospel Mission in
Portland, the Disabled Businesspersons Association in San Diego,
and the Resources, Inc. program in Brooklyn -- the Samaritan Award
winners who are here today.  I've read their reports.  Challenging,
personal, spiritual.  Not easy.  Not easy at all, but possible.
<p>
I have personally seen some successes over the years.  I've seen
lives of pregnant, unmarried women turned around.  I've seen abandoned
children happily adopted.  I've seen failures.  Recently, I was
working with a homeless ex-con.  I thought that he was making
good progress, but now he has slipped back into irresponsibility.
He's in jail right now.  He's having a hearing next week.  Maybe
he'll get out and have another start.  I sent him over to the
most challenging shelter in Austin, Texas the same day I sent
my oldest son to college.  But my homeless friend, Fred, just
lasted three days at the shelter, and then he went back out on
the streets and is now in jail.  My son is still at the University
of Texas.
<p>
So, it's not easy, but it is possible.  People do change.  God
changed me.  He moved me out of the Marxism that I adhered to
25 years ago.  He brought me to a knowledge of Christ, and I'm
thankful to Him.  Other people can change.  You see it all the
time, and there's lots of experience in the room testifying to
that as well.
<p>
<center><h3>TOWARD A THEOLOGY OF CHARITY</h3></center>
<p>
But in order to really have confidence that this change can occur,
we have to do a couple of things.  And they're not primarily political.
The first thing we have to do is just awaken ourselves theologically
and put God's principles to work.  Only after that do we have
to start working on some public policy matters.
<p>
There is a lot of false gospel that's being offered now.  There
are those on the religious left who say that the Bible mandates
the government transfers of resources to the poor on the grounds
of, for example, Jesus' statement, &quot;Whatever you did to the
least of these, brethren, you did to Me.&quot;  Now I take that
verse very seriously.  But before we blindly use it to justify
the welfare state, we need to ask who are the least of these in
America?  What kind of help is real help?  Certainly, children
threatened with death before birth by abortion are among the least
of these, and I would love for all of the groups on the Christian
left that have been proclaiming so vociferously their love for
the unwanted, the poor, and the neglected to really work hard
on abortion.  Women abandoned by their husbands, children who
grow up without fathers.  They also have it very rough and the
concern should be: How do you give them hope?  How do you break
out of that fatalism?
<p>
But what about able-bodied homeless men?  One of the prime changes
in the welfare legislation that is chugging through Congress,
shortly to hit President Clinton's desk, is a cut (actually a
real cut) in aid to homeless men who are addicts or alcoholics.
Here's a hard case.  Here's something that I think obviously
should be changed.  Does irresponsibility qualify a person for
the ranks of the least of these?  Jesus does not include in his
list of commended charitable acts, &quot;When I was strung out,
you gave me dope.&quot;  If we take seriously Christ's words in
Matthew 25, &quot;Whatever you did to the least of these, my brethren,
you did to Me,&quot; then giving money that goes for drugs is
akin to sticking heroin into Jesus' veins.  So rather than proclaiming
the dire effect of cuts generally -- instead of rushing into the
guns at Cold Harbor -- why not accurately and carefully look at
some of these measures and say, &quot;Aha, this is something that
really should be cut&quot;?  Instead, we're not really getting
to that level of specific detail.  Instead, we're just hearing
the blanket condemnations of any movement away from the status
quo as if anything at all, any change at all, is an indication
of hardheartedness.
<p>
Well, if we straighten out the theology, the practice follows.
When I was a Marxist, I believed in top-down approaches, emphasizing
government redistribution.  But as a Christian, I understand that
change comes one by one from the inside out.  Straighten out the
theology of those who are rich, and there will be a tremendous
expansion of effective compassion.  Straighten out the theology
of those who are economically poor because of poor values, and
their attitudes and behaviors will change.  And they will make
progress.  So the essence here is revival and reformation among
both rich and poor.  That will transform American poverty-fighting.
There would be such an outpouring of private charity, if we had
that revival and reformation, that governmental programs could
rapidly be replaced.  We would not even have to debate the question
of tax credits for charitable contributions.
<p>
<center><h3>PUBLIC POLICY, POVERTY, AND THE PREAMBLE</h3></center>
<p>
But while we can hope and pray for revival and reformation, it's
not something that we can count on.  And so here we do come to
questions of public policy.  I'd suggest that a firm distinction
that needs to be made is the constitutional distinction between
&quot;providing&quot; and &quot;promoting.&quot;  The Constitution
talks about &quot;providing&quot; for the common defense, but
&quot;promoting&quot; the general welfare.  There's such a huge
difference between, say, renting a hall for a convention and manning
every booth in that hall yourself.  That's the difference between
providing and promoting.  We're in the mess we're in right now
because the government has attempted to provide welfare, and instead
it has given us entitlements and bureaucracy.  There's a legitimate
role for government, promoting the general welfare, but not providing.
<p>
That's where we come to this question of tax credits on either
a state or national level.  Frankly, I'd rather see it done on
a state-by-state level because we don't know exactly what the
best tax credit mechanism is.  The best way will promote discerning
giving on the part of individuals while avoiding government entanglement
with religious and other charities as much as possible.  We don't
know whether a hundred percent tax credit is absolutely the best
thing, or whether a 90 percent tax credit would generate just
about the same amount of income for private and church charities.
But a 90 percent tax credit would encourage considerably more
discernment on the part of givers because they'd be putting up,
let's say, a hundred dollars of their own money on a thousand
dollar contribution.  They might think a little more seriously
about where it's going.
<p>
I'm also worried about credits without any personal involvement.
It would be much better if we could offer tax credits only to
the individuals who also spend some time at the charities to which
they are giving.  The bookkeeping in that may be too complicated.
It may not work.  But I'd actually prefer to see things go on
a state-by-state basis so we would have some experiments.  Tax
credits, I think, are a very good idea.  And the constitutional
questions of interference with religious groups can be resolved.
If you have a coalition strong enough to pass tax credits, you
have a coalition strong enough to protect religious groups from
federal interference.
<p>
There is no reason, in fact, why you can't have a national approach
and state approaches at the same time, trying out different things
over these next few years to see what will best promote community-based,
poverty-fighting charities.  What I don't understand is why some
of the big philanthropic and charitable groups are not getting
on the team for tax measures to encourage giving.  You'd think
that they would be eager for such a reform, or else they're just
in the position of saying &quot;no, no, no&quot; to any change,
more and more vehemently.  I'd challenge those big charities like
Catholic Charities, but others also.  Why don't they propose something
positive instead of defending to the death a failed status quo?
If their concern is adequate funding for poverty programs, why
not tax credits?  Or else you have to start raising the question:
Are they more concerned about the poor, or about holding on to
their own power?  I'm not sure.  Everyone I've met from those
organizations is well-intentioned, but they've grown so used to
kissing up to government officials instead of going to individual
taxpayers and making the case to them that they deserve support.
Well, I don't know, but it's a problem.  It's a sad state of
affairs.
<p>
There are people who say, well, any other alternative just simply
will not work.  I was reading the other day about the case of
a student of management named Fred Smith, who went on to found
Federal Express.  And he described, in a term paper, his idea
for a reliable overnight delivery service.  His professor gave
him a &quot;C&quot; and explained that the concept was interesting
and well-formed.  &quot;But in order to earn better than a 'C,'&quot;
he said, &quot;the idea must be feasible.&quot;  Charity tax credit
proposals are feasible.  We need to experiment a little bit, but
we need to fight for them.  And we need to push the big philanthropies
and the big philanthropic trade organizations like Independent
Sector and the Council on Foundations to support them also.
<p>
This public policy stuff is important, but the tendency -- especially
here in Washington -- is to fall into the trap of thinking that
a particular piece of legislation is the solution.  Charity tax
credits are a great mechanism to take money off the top of the
governmental superstructure and stick it back on the bottom in
private and religious charities where it can do the most good.
But it's still just a mechanism.  The more time I spend in Washington,
the more I feel as if I'm reading from a manual for medical emergencies
put together by people whose goals exceed their wisdom.  This
is like a recommendation from a student in a junior high school
science class for a nose bleed: Put the nose much lower than the
body until the heart stops.
<p>
The public policy change is essential, but we can't wait for that.
Again, I am somewhat aghast at the thought of mentioning this
to some of you who have done so much over the years.  You know
the answer to this question very well because you've lived it.
But the question is: How does each of us individually help children
and adults now one by one?  How do we create models for the way
the entire welfare system can be transformed and replaced?  What
first steps can those of us in this room take?
<p>
<center><h3>TAKING FIRST STEPS</h3></center>
<p>
Especially in this group, I'm nervous about mentioning any of
the things that my wife and I have been involved in, but they've
been educational for us.  And again, as a number of you who know
me know, I am not always the most diplomatic person around.  Frederica
Mathewes-Green knows.  She is one of our national correspondents
at <I>World</I> magazine, and so she and I discuss editorial matters
and stories occasionally.  I want to be kind of a hard-nosed editor
at times, and so I tend not to be the nicest guy around.  My wife
is a much better person than I am in that regard.  But I tend
to think, okay, as bullheaded as I am, I have been able with my
wife to give a room in our home to needy individuals, to coach
kids in baseball, to tutor children, to mentor some folks, and
to adopt a child.  If I -- not a particularly hospitable individual,
a guy who would rather spend time in the bowels of the Library
of Congress than actually helping someone directly -- if I once
and awhile can do something a little bit decent, why can't people
with much greater merits, with much greater abilities and niceness
and goodness, do the same or even much more?
<p>
I know that many of you already give of yourselves a lot.  Can
you do even more?  Again, some of you I know are just working
already to the max.  Some of you have not probably been involved
with the poor at all.  Will you take a first step?  Just think
for a moment.  If I were a liberal, I would want you to close
your eyes and visualize world peace.  As it is, I want you to
visualize in your mind's eye one poor person whom you have directly,
personally helped during the past year.  A lot of you, I'm sure,
can do that and can probably visualize lots and lots of people.
If you don't see anyone, I pray that you'll take a small step
during 1996, and maybe then even a larger one: tutoring a child
for one hour a week, being a big brother or big sister, or Little
League coach, mentoring an adult who's gotten in trouble, providing
Biblical counsel to a young, unmarried pregnant woman, maybe giving
her a room in your home, maybe adopting a child.  Those steps
are hard, but we're surrounded.  We are just so surrounded by
a great cloud of witnesses, men and women like ourselves who have
taken first steps and then many more.  This is what I have learned
by going around the country this year.
<p>
Remember chapters 11 and 12 of Hebrews talking about the great
cloud of witnesses?  Hebrews 12:1 says, &quot;Therefore, since
we are surrounded by a great cloud of witnesses, let us lay aside
every weight.  Let us run with patience the race that is set before
us.&quot;  Let's work theologically, let's work politically, let's
work personally.  As we work and pray, let's remember that 2,000
years ago Jesus Christ came into the world to suffer with us,
to die for us, and in this year of our Lord 1995 it is such a
great blessing to see godly people who follow in His steps.
<p>
It was six years ago, just before Christmas 1989, that I began
trying in my own real small way to resurrect the word &quot;compassion&quot;
among conservatives and to promote some compassionate alternatives
to failed welfare programs.  I gave a talk six years ago at the
Heritage Foundation, and I just ran across a copy in my files
a couple of days ago while thinking about what I would say here
today.  I gave it at the time when I was in the middle of my historical
research at the Library of Congress.  But it still seems relevant
to me, and I haven't talked about this for a long time.  Let me
just read the ending of that talk:
<p>
<blockquote><i>It's beginning to look a lot like Christmas.  A time when 
God came to earth to teach, to suffer, and to save by suffering. 
A generation ago, Whittaker Chambers wrote that 'suffering is
at the heart of every living faith.  That is why a man can scarcely
call himself a Christian for whom the crucifixion is not a daily
suffering.'  Chambers knew that Christianity is rooted in suffering.
I would add 'suffering with.'  But he recognized that the meaning
of the faith 'has been blurred as Christianity, in common with
the voices of a new age, seeks new escapes from the problem of
suffering.  Nothing is more characteristic of this age than its
obsession with an avoidance of suffering.'  Are we in America,
and conservatives especially, serious people?  Frankly, I do not
always know whether I am.  I do not know whether you are.  I hope
we are.  I pray that we are, but I do not know.  I do not know,
but finding out is the challenge of the 1990s for the conservative
movement.</i></blockquote>
<p>
That was what I was saying in 1989.  Now it's 1995, and we've
made some progress.  The battle for the word &quot;compassion,&quot;
the understanding of compassion, is now on.  But the body count
is growing.  Those bodies that are Cold Harbors all over the inner
cities of this country are just piling up.  And the defenders
of this status quo are tenacious.  At least we're in the fight.
It's hard, but it's glorious.  I've been glad to be fighting
alongside a lot of you this year.  And I pray that that will continue
and that we will overcome with God's grace.
<p>
Thank you very much.
<p>
-- 2/1/96
<p>
<center>***</center>
<p>
<i>Dr. Olasky is Senior Fellow and Progress and Freedom Foundation,
where he is studying the most effective methods for assisting
the truly needy, and designing replacements for the current welfare
state.  He is the co-founder of the Center for Effective Compassion,
inspired by his landmark work in the study of charity,</i> The
Tragedy of American Compassion. <i>He is currently writing a
sequel,</i> The Promise of American Compassion.

<p>

