<html>

<title>CHRISTIAN COMMUNITY DEVELOPMENT</title>

<body>

<center><img src="/townhall/FRC/podium/podium.gif">

<h2>CHRISTIAN COMMUNITY<br>
DEVELOPMENT</h2>

<p><hr size=3 width=50%><p>

<i>by<br>
Dr. John M. Perkins</i></center>

<p>

<i>The following speech was presented at the Family Research Council's
&quot;World Without Welfare&quot; symposium on December 13, 1995
at the Willard Hotel in Washington, D.C.</i>

<p>

Wayne Gordon and I are going across America in something that
we are calling the American Cities Campaign.  We are taking into
cities across the country the concepts of neighborhood and community
development that have emerged from the church.  I am the chairman
of the Christian Community Development Association, and Wayne
Gordon is the president.  He has spent 20 years in Chicago developing
ministries there.  His great ministry has been building up Lawndale
Community, one of the 15 poorest neighborhoods in America.  Because
of efforts by people like Wayne Gordon, young, indigenous people
-- predominantly black -- are going off to colleges and universities
and returning to their home communities to provide new leadership
for a new generation.

<p>

<center><h3>SUGGESTED RESOURCES</h3></center>

<p>

Wayne Gordon has described his effort in a book called <I>Real
Hope in Chicago</I>.

<p>

The book that best summarizes the philosophy that I will share
with you today, however, is a book called <I>Beyond Charity</I>.
This book outlines how we have been working for the last 35 years
in neighborhood and community development.  And a new textbook
for community development today has just been published under
the title <I>Restoring At-Risk Communities</I>.  I edited the
book, but it was written by practitioners -- people who are a
part of the Christian Community Development Association (CCDA).

<p>

The Christian Community Development Association is made up of
about 4,000 individuals and about 400 organizations.  The purpose
is really not something from the top down; it's something from
the bottom up.  It belongs to the people, one of the things that
motivated me to come here today.  I don't really believe that
major organizations, whether they're government organizations
or national organizations, can implement indigenous leadership and 
produce the kind of motivation and incentive that people need at the 
bottom.

<p>

We do need organizations that affirm the dignity of the people.
The rationale for a national organization ought to be to inspire
those people to take responsibility for their own lives.  Then
we can come along beside them to help them realize their hopes,
goals, and aspirations.  I think you have heard today that our
big federal government is taking that incentive away.  I think
that's what's motivating the movement for welfare reform.  You
can't isolate crime and violence and all these other problems
from the fact that well-intended people are doing things without
believing in the inherent dignity of the individuals being helped.

<p>

The programs that work are those programs in which the initiative
starts first with the people themselves.  Alcoholics Anonymous
is working.  It is working because the individual says &quot;the
problem is mine&quot; and decides to take responsibility for himself.
Then other people come along beside him and help.  Our work should
be to bring about that kind of motivation, incentive, creativity
and the hope that people can do for themselves what they need
to do.  Our newest book, <I>Restoring At-Risk Communities,</I> outlines
strategies for success.

<p>

The last book I want to mention specifically is <I>Resurrecting
Hope</I>.  We have looked at 12 churches in America that have
taken the principles that I am talking about in terms of community
development and have put those principles to work at the grass-roots
level.  There's a West Los Angeles church, for example, that is
the largest black worshipping congregation in the United States.
I worked with that church, and they are in the book.  There is
also Redeemer Presbyterian Church in New York City, along with
10 other congregations that are doing successful community development
work.

<p>

Finally, we have created <I>Urban Family</I> magazine because
we were concerned about the philosophy of the liberal establishment.
I am not stating that fact to pit liberals against conservatives.
I object to liberalism simply because the system created by the
liberal establishment has made black people think of ourselves
as helpless victims who cannot do much for ourselves -- despite
the fact that people like Booker T. Washington and others came
out of slavery and developed the great institutions of our day.

<p>

We now have all the resources, but we act like victims because
the government has come in and taken the responsibility away from
people.  We fault racism and everything else for all of our problems,
and we never play to our advantages.  And so we created a magazine
called <I>Urban Family</I>. It looks at people in the community
who have taken the initiative and are doing things very creatively,
and it encourages blacks to begin building on our strengths instead
of just compounding our weaknesses and always acting like victims.

<p>

There is no other national Christian magazine that is written
from a black perspective in America.  The voices and the aspirations
of black folks themselves are not being heard -- we hear only
the liberal-victimization type of mentality that is being spoken
for us by somebody else in society.  And so this magazine is published
from the urban community, by people within the urban community.

<p>

The last publication that I want to mention is our newest magazine,
called <I>Reconciliation</I>.  Of course, one of our operating
assumptions -- even as we talk today about the church taking responsibility
for the problem -- is that the church itself has a major problem.
The problem is that the church has lost its central message of
the Gospel, which is the love of God <I>demonstrated</I>.  The
purpose of the Gospel is to reconcile alienated humanity to a
holy God and to each other across racial, social, and economic
barriers.

<p>

But instead we have created a church that perpetuates those barriers,
and that's the reason that all our social action has not yet prevailed
against racial division. The church is essentially operating as
a black church or a white church or a Chinese church -- which,
again, is a major heresy because the very idea of the Gospel was
to reconcile those people together in one body and the world would
know that we were Christians because of our love one for another.
If we take all the money from the federal government and somehow
shift all responsibilities to the local church, we still would
not have solved our problem.  We still would not be able to communicate
the central message of the Gospel -- that the world will know
we are Christians by our love.

<p>

<center><h3>PHILOSOPHICAL FOUNDATION</h3></center>

<p>

So let me just share with you a little bit about the philosophy
on which our ministry is based.  Our ministry is based on the
fact that we are created in the very image of God.   This must
be the first effort of Christians -- to establish that all people
are created in the image of God, that all people therefore have
dignity, and that our dealings with each other should reflect
that sense of divinely-endowed dignity.  But how do we affirm
the dignity of individuals?  If we affirm the dignity of people,
then we can create the motivation and incentive for their own
development in society.  So how do you do that?  How do you meet
people where they live?

<p>

You must meet people at their basic need as they perceive it.
That's why uniform government programs organized in Washington
by task forces and imposed on people down at the community level
are going to further cripple people because top-down programs
do not represent their greatest aspirations.  We need to start
with the deepest felt needs of people.  Then we need to love those
people around those needs as they perceive them before we try
to change them.  Our loving them, in other words, is the change
agent.  We cannot change anyone before we choose to love him as
he is.

<p>

If you affirm dignity by meeting people at their deepest felt
needs, then we can motivate them.  That's why Jesus became bread
to people who were hungry.  That's why He became water to people
who were thirsty.  He met people at their basic need.  He loved
them around that need, and you can't do that from afar.  The felt-need
concept, then, is the basic philosophy that grounds community
development.  We are not necessarily accepting wrong behavior.
Instead, we are accepting that behavior as an expression of their
need at the time and then loving them until we can motivate them
to see that they have a deeper need that will require a change
in their lives.

<p>

How do you implement that change?  Let's look at the three basic
human needs that people have in society.

<p>

<center><h3>THREE BASIC HUMAN NEEDS</h3></center>

<p>

The most basic need that people have is the need to be loved and
nurtured.  We know that fact by observing broken families that
are lacking in love and nurture.  If you ask most people who study
urban crime, they will tell you that the vast majority of juvenile
delinquents come from a home without a father -- without that
early childhood nurture.

<p>

The second need that people have is the need to know that they
are significant.  Human beings are not &quot;niggers,&quot; 
&quot;honkies,&quot; and &quot;gooks.&quot;  Human beings were created in 
the image of God and have absolute dignity.  That dignity needs to be 
expressed in their own creativity.  Their own creativity is work.  Work
is absolutely crucial to the reflection of God's image.  God worked,
and He created us to express His dignity by our own creativity
and our own work.

<p>

The third need is the need for a reasonable amount of security.
Everybody has that basic need.  The most crucial problem in our
society is not simply the breakdown of the family, although that
in itself is a reflection of the problem.   The great problem
we have in our society is the breakdown of the community itself.
Families break down from time to time.  But when the community
breaks down, then the society falls apart.  Most social or government
action doesn't really get at the crux of the problem because it
is dealing with symptoms of the problem.  In reality, it takes
the village to raise the child and so we need to re-fix the village.
Mankind was created to live together in a neighborhood, the perfect
village.  So how do you tend to the village?  How do you develop
the community?

<p>

When I arrived in Mississippi, I realized that our education and
social welfare system did not affirm dignity.  Education merely
transported young folks out of the village, leaving the community
poorer and poorer as they went away.  The greatest problem we
have today is that people with the skills remove themselves from
the places of need -- and in their absence, we send in our welfare
system to make the needy dependent.  People need our presence
in the neighborhood with them.  They need our inspiration.

<p>

I can see that in Mendenhall.  I remember saying to my wife Vera
Mae 30 years ago, &quot;We're going to make a difference in this
little village of Mendenhall, this little poverty village.  What
we have to do is stay in this little village long enough so that
we can win some of these young people to Jesus Christ.  We have
to be able to nurture them in their faith.  We have to help them
get a love for God, a love for themselves and a love for the community.
That's a greater love than consumerism and materialism.  Then
we will help them to go off to college and to secure an education
with a purpose.  We will teach them to get the education and then
return with their new-found knowledge to help develop the resources
of the community.&quot;

<p>

I stayed in that community 12 years.  It happened.  I left there
and went to Jackson, and I stayed in that community for 10 years.
It happened there, too.   And then I went to California and stayed
in a neighborhood for 13 years.  My own children there have developed
a school in that community to carry on and to educate those children
within that neighborhood.  So, it is possible.  But our concept
of development must be &quot;indigenous.&quot;  First, we must
plant ourselves within the community.  The reason Wayne Gordon
has succeeded in Chicago is that he moved into that neighborhood
20 years ago and has lived there, inspiring people day by day.

<p>

<center><h3>THREE &quot;R'S&quot;</h3></center>

<p>

So the first &quot;R&quot; in development is <I>relocation</I>,
living in the community with the people.  The people in the community
must be able to take responsibility for their own lives.  Outside
people must come in if necessary to live among them and to inspire
individuals to take responsibility for their own lives.   Then,
those individuals in turn will have the joy of developing their
own neighborhood in their own community.  This approach to redevelopment
will take a generation to accomplish.  But you must live in the
neighborhood.  You can do some hopeful, nice things; but if you
are not living in the neighborhood, you may be convincing the
poor that they do not have worth.  You may be creating more violence
within them and giving them false hope.

<p>

The second &quot;R&quot; of development is <I>reconciliation</I>.
If the church does not believe in that, our country will be hopelessly
divided.  The new leader in the black community is a black Muslim
who does not believe that the Gospel is to reconcile people together.
The rise of Islam will aggravate racial tensions -- unless the
white congregation recalls to its senses the fact that the purpose
of the Gospel is to reconcile man to God and man to man.

<p>

The third &quot;R&quot; of development is something I call 
<I>redistribution</I>. By the word &quot;redistribution,&quot; I don't 
mean taking all the money from the rich and giving it to the poor because 
that would only mean that we have deified money.  Deifying money is
a basic problem in our society and a central problem of government.
Even a tax credit for charitable contributions runs the risk
of deifying money.  Remember that tax money didn't originally
belong to the government.  It originally belonged to the people,
and it is the responsibility of the government to manage those
resources for the greater good of society.  The first need that
people have is not money, but incentive.  They need the incentive
of community before they get money.  They need motivation.  They
need education.  They need skills, and all of these are more important
than money.

<p>

If the churches become contractors for the government, moreover,
this will be a disaster for our nation at the most fundamental
level.  I do believe that the church can inspire economic and
all other kinds of development at the grass-roots.  But if you
have churches competing for government money -- and every day
in the newspapers there is another church that, like government
poverty programs, has used the money poorly -- we will have destroyed
the last life we have within the urban community and the last
healing program we have.

<p>

Those programs that are really healing in the community are not
those that are funded by the government.  Those programs that
are really healing people are ones that have taken the initiative
and have been able to put together the private resources to do
the kind of work that the Christian Community Development Association
encompasses.

<p>

On the other hand, I would be in favor of programs like vouchers
for schools or other services.  At least the vouchers would be
based more on production and creative competition -- unlike block
grants, where the resources would be quickly wasted and swallowed.
The public schools are too big and the classrooms are too clumsy
to give nurture or cultivate Christian values at the community
level.  And in our community, we must have the motivating force
of faith.

<p>

Faith-based discussions build on the dignity and the historical
behavior of black people in our society.  The discussion of faith
must take place -- or else, we are destined still to be driven
by racism and bigotry.  And our people will still suffer.

<p>
-- 12/13/95
<p>

<center>***</center>

<p>

<i>Dr. John Perkins is a longtime champion of biblical justice
and the economic development of the black community.  He founded
Mendenhall Ministries in Mendenhall, Mississippi and with others
established the Christian Community Development Association, Voice
of Calvary Ministries in Jackson, Mississippi, and Harambee Christian
Family Center, an after-school mentoring program in Northwest
Pasadena, Calif.  He is the founder and publisher of </I>Urban
Family <I>magazine and the author of several books, including</I>
Beyond Charity.  <I>To contact Dr. Perkins, or to order books,
please call (818) 791-7439.</I>

<p>

<center>
