<title>HUMAN RIGHTS ABUSES HAVE WORSENED</title>

<body>

<center><img src="/townhall/FRC/podium/podium.gif">

<h2>HUMAN RIGHTS ABUSES HAVE<br>
WORSENED SINCE CHINA<br>
RECEIVED MFN STATUS</h2>

<p><hr size=3 width=50%><p>

<h4>Testimony of Gracie S. Hsu, Policy Analyst<br>
Family Research Council<br>
Submitted to the House Committee on International Relations<br>
Subcommittee on International Operations and Human Rights<br>
June 18, 1996</h4></center>

<p>

Mr. Chairman, the Family Research Council is pleased that the
Subcommittee on International Operations and Human Rights has
chosen to address the human rights consequences of extending &quot;most
favored nation&quot; (MFN) trade privileges to China.  This hearing
is especially timely considering the fact that the House of Representatives
is scheduled to vote on legislation regarding China's MFN status
in the coming week.

<p>

Mr. Chairman, for 15 years, the United States has extended &quot;most
favored nation&quot; trade status to China.  Originally, it had
been argued that an economic &quot;open door&quot; might encourage
the Chinese government to shape up their human rights policies,
but in these past 15 years, we have only seen the barbarity and
cruelty of this communist regime increase.

<p>

Thus, the Family Research Council strongly urges Congress to pass
legislation revoking China's &quot;most favored nation&quot; trade
status because of China's continuing human rights abuses.

<p>

It was seven years ago when 700 Chinese democracy-seekers were
ruthlessly gunned down at Tiananmen Square.  It was only last
year when Hong Kong newspapers reported that aborted human fetuses
were being cannibalized in China, sold as health food.  Last September,
directly before the United Nations Fourth World Conference on
Women in Beijing, the Chinese government executed nine prisoners
to &quot;send a message&quot; to their own people that they should
not attempt to demonstrate against the Chinese government.

<p>

In addition to these &quot;newer&quot; human rights violations,
other abuses which existed in China prior to their receiving MFN
status continue to go unabated.  For example, the Chinese government
continues to exploit prisoners for slave labor in their gulag
system known as &quot;laogai,&quot; as Harry Wu has demonstrated.
Mr. Chairman, it is these same slaves which make many of the
products which China exports for profit.

<p>

Furthermore, Chinese women continue to be forcibly aborted and/or
involuntarily sterilized.  It is well documented that women, even
in their eighth and ninth months of pregnancy, have been literally
dragged from their homes by &quot;family planning&quot; officials,
tied down with their feet in stirrups, and forcibly aborted.

<p>

China's one-child-per-couple mandate has also led to widespread
sex selection abortion, and unborn baby girls are most often the
innocent victims of this crime against humanity.  But even for
those little girls who are born alive, many are immediately abandoned
by their parents.  China has chosen to deal with this &quot;problem&quot;
of abandoned children by starving the little girls to death in
state-run orphanages.

<p>

Religious persecution also continues to abound in China.  As Family
Research Council President Gary Bauer testified before this Subcommittee
in February, Christians are systematically intimidated, tortured
and imprisoned in China.  Indeed, Amnesty International reports
cases of Christian women hung by their thumbs from wires and beaten
with heavy rods, denied food and water, and shocked with electric
probes.

<p>

These, Mr. Chairman, are crimes against humanity.  These are the
brutal and unjust actions of a communist regime to which our nation
has extended &quot;most favored nation&quot; trade privileges
for 15 years.

<p>

The failure of the United States to hold China accountable for
its heinous behavior has only encouraged the communist regime
to become more oppressive because it no longer fears that any
sanctions will be taken against it.  Year after year, the United
States has issued only empty threats against the Chinese government,
and in doing so, we have strained our credibility and undercut
our own stature as a moral leader in the world.  Indeed, the U.S.
has sent the shameful message that, as a country, we care more
about succeeding economically than about championing universal
human rights.

<p>

It is time for the United States to put teeth to our convictions
and revoke China's &quot;most favored nation&quot; trade privileges.

<p>

<center>***</center>

<p>

<i>Gracie S. Hsu, M.H.S., is a policy analyst at
the Family Research Council, a Washington, D.C.-based research
and educational organization.</i>

<p>

